post_text:
Does your child receive free or reduced-price school meals during the school year, or do you believe you may now qualify based on a recent income change?

Pandemic-EBT, or P-EBT, can help you feed your family while schools are closed. You will receive a card with approximately $279 per eligible child that you can use to purchase food at stores that accept EBT. If you already receive SNAP benefits and are eligible for P-EBT, these funds will automatically load into your existing account. If you do not currently receive SNAP benefits, apply here for P-EBT today: https://www.colorado.gov/cdhs/p-ebt.

Check your child’s Parent Portal or Student Portal inbox for the SASID number required in the application. If you need Parent or Student Portal assistance, please call (970) 252-7918.

shared_text:
City of Montrose Colorado Government
May 16 at 4:36 PM ·

Earlier this week, school administrators and parents of the class of 2020 graduates, placed pictures of each graduate on the Montrose High School football field in tribute to this year’s graduates who had their senior year cut short by the COVID-19 pandemic.
Graduation is tomorrow May 17, and instead of walking across a stage to receive their diplomas, graduates will be separated, and driven individually in cars in line to receive their diplomas.
Graduation weekend in Montrose has always been a big weekend for this community as we celebrate another year and another class of kids moving on from school. We are all proud of the class of 2020 and wish them luck in the future.
#montroseco
text:
City of Montrose Colorado Government
May 16 at 4:36 PM ·

Earlier this week, school administrators and parents of the class of 2020 graduates, placed pictures of each graduate on the Montrose High School football field in tribute to this year’s graduates who had their senior year cut short by the COVID-19 pandemic.
Graduation is tomorrow May 17, and instead of walking across a stage to receive their diplomas, graduates will be separated, and driven individually in cars in line to receive their diplomas.
Graduation weekend in Montrose has always been a big weekend for this community as we celebrate another year and another class of kids moving on from school. We are all proud of the class of 2020 and wish them luck in the future.
#montroseco

May 11 at 2:39 PM ·

6th grade going on now....END OF THE YEAR INFORMATION>.
Dear Centennial Parents and Students,

The end of the school year is upon us, the week of May 11th will be setup to collect student iPads in IMC, band instruments, hand out yearbooks, collect wrestling jerseys, and clean out student lockers. All belongings that are not picked up in lockers will be collected and donated. We will be limiting the number of students entering at one time. We would ask that students wear face masks to follow the social distancing practices. The schedule will be as follows:
Monday May 11th - 6th grade 7:30am-3:30pm
Tuesday May 12th – 7th grade 7:30am-3:30pm
Wednesday May 13th – 8th grade 7:30am-3:30pm

We thank you for your cooperation and look forward to seeing you,
Centennial Staff

post_text:
The Montrose County School District School Board is pleased to announce Dr. Carrie Stephenson as the next superintendent of schools.

School Board President, Gayle Johnson states “The School Board was privileged to have three qualified finalists to consider for the position. We feel that Carrie will bring a unique set of qualities and characteristics to our district. We look forward to continued growth and improvement under her leadership.”

The search began with focus groups to gain input on what the board, district search committee and community would like to see in a new superintendent.

Three final candidates were chosen from a pool of 12 applicants.

Carrie is the current Area Superintendent for the Douglas County School District in Castle Rock, Colorado. She has been in education for 30 years, serving as a teacher, Assistant Principal, and Principal.

The nationwide search was conducted by the Colorado Association of School Board Superintendent Search team. Dr. Carrie Stephenson will take over the position on July 1, 2020.

We know it is hard to remain socially distanced, but we highly discourage parents from sending children to sleepovers, play dates, or other gatherings at this time. It is important to remember that children may not be symptomatic, but still could be carrying the virus. The sleepovers or other gatherings could cause spread back to the homes of parents and risk additional community spread.

The administration of end-of-the-year assessments, including the Colorado Measures of Academic Success (CMAS), will be paused for the remainder of the 2019-20 school year due to extensive school closures throughout Colorado to prevent the spread of COVID-19, Colorado Education Commissioner Katy Anthes announced today.

CDE is working with The College Board to generate possible solutions for the administration of the PSAT and SAT tests, which offer unique roles in Colorado’s system in terms of scholarships and college entrance. Additional information will come from CDE as it becomes available.

https://www.cde.state.co.us/communications/20200317stateassessments

post_text:
Montrose County School District has made the decision to close all schools in the district effective today, March 13th through the end of Spring Break, April 12th. The status of the district will be re-evaluated by that time to determine if school can resume.

This decision was made out of an abundance of caution for our students, staff and community as at this time, there are no confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Montrose County. This decision was made in collaboration with Montrose County Public Health, County Commissioners, County Sheriff, The City of Montrose and Montrose Police to ensure that all of our community stays healthy and safe.

Continue to watch the District web site (www.mcsd.org) and Facebook page as well as the Montrose County Public Health Department web site (www.montrosecounty.net/940/Public-Health) for updated information.

Additional information will be reported on Tuesday, March 17th on next steps.

Once every 10 years, we get an opportunity to shape the future of our schools and community. By adding your voice to the 2020 Census! An accurate count is critical to our schools and community. Your response to the 2020 Census will drive decisions from Washington D.C. on the annual allocation of more the $675 Billion in federal funds to states, local communities, and to our schools.

Beginning in March 2020 you will be able to have everyone in your home be counted, this will help drive federal funds to Montrose County. You can be counted by doing this online, by phone, or by mail. Go to 2020CENSUS.GOV to learn how to be counted!

COVID-19: What is my risk?

Montrose Police Department
February 27 at 3:09 AM ·

⚠️SHARE⚠️: There are NO cases of #COVID19 (Coronavirus Disease-19) in Montrose County.

COVID-19: How can I help protect myself?

We recommend everyday preventive actions to help prevent the spread of respiratory viruses, including:
•Avoid close contact with people who are sick.
•Avoid touching eyes, nose, and mouth.
•Wash hands with soap and water for at least 20 seconds.
•Clean and disinfect frequently touched objects and surfaces.
•Get a flu shot (it's not too late, and the MCPH clinic has vaccine available).

post_text:
Superintendent Search Interview Committee Applications now Available

Applications are now available to apply to be a member of the Interview Committee in the upcoming Superintendent Search. You can print an application from the main page of the website (www.mcsd.org), the district Facebook page (@montrosecountyschooldistrict) or pick up at the District Office, located at 930 Colorado Avenue, Montrose.

Applications must be returned no later than February 28th for review and selection by the school board.

Please contact Laurie Laird at 970-252-7902 or laurie.laird@mcsd.org if you have additional questions.

UPDATE Tuesday, January 21, 2020 10:35 am

Northside Elementary and Peak Academy were under shelter-in-place due to police activity in the area. This event lasted 10 minutes and was found to be noise from a blown transformer.
